Lagos – The Confederation of African Football (CAF) has given Ghana strict conditions for use of the Baba Yara Stadium for the first leg of the 2022 FIFA World Cup qualifying playoff against Nigeria on Friday, March 25. However, if these conditions are not met, the match will still be played at the stadium, but Ghana FA will suffer unstated financial penalties. The decision to relocate the match to Kumasi was sequel to the inspection of CAF team, which found the Cape Coast stadium unworthy of hosting the match. But CAF, while approving the use of Kumasi stadium, insisted that Ghana must install a new international standard, modern and comfortable official’ benches at pitch level; they must also adjust the floodlight intensity by providing a minimum of 1200 Lux all over the pitch, covering uniformly every area of the playing field. The FA among others also asked to increase the seating and lockers in the teams dressing rooms to reach (25) persons; Installation of completely new modern equipment and materials in the referees dressing rooms and ensure that it is equipped with all the necessary materials and CAF requirements; Set up the water system to provide both cold and hot water in the teams and officials dressing rooms; General refurbishment of the CAF office, installation of modern desks and seats, including the necessary electronic and working equipment; VOC must be available and equipped with all the necessary equipment and requirements; Complete refurbishment of the media tribune, press conference room and media centre, installing new and modern equipment. CAF promised to inspect the stadium even it will be on the day of the match so as to ensure that all the above-mentioned facilities were provided. The game initially scheduled for the Cape Coast Sports Stadium on March 25 was relocated to the Baba Yara Stadium due to the poor state of the pitch. While confirming these new developments on Wednesday, Ghana FA noted, “The Confederation of African Football has granted a one match approval for Baba Yara Sports Stadium in Kumasi to host the World Cup Qatar 2022 play-off match between Ghana and Nigeria.